    "Cross-validation answers that by not picking just one. It cuts the data into K equal slices (\"folds\"), then trains K times: each fold takes one turn as the test set while the other K−1 folds train. You get K scores; their average is a far steadier estimate of how the model does on unseen data — and every point gets tested exactly once.\n",
